Description: The Comments Section is a website that culls together interesting comments found in the internet and adds their own commentary.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Miami Area, East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Here's the straight dope: our website is called TheCommentsSection.com and, yes, it's devoted to the Interweb's many comment sections. Why? Well, because comment sections are mostly unmoderated public fora that remind us of the old, wild west: they're lawless, dangerous, and itchy. They've made us laugh, made us cry, and they've given us Cholera. We think it's about time that someone held a mirror up to comment sections to show that comment sections (defined both by anonymity and immediacy) offer us a cross-section of human interaction on the Web -- for better and for worse. Comment sections are a free-for-all and, as such, they offer us a telling glimpse into our behavior in a modern, digital democracy. So, we're taking it upon ourselves to cull together the funniest, craziest, and most offensive of these public galleries for your amusement and edification. We then add our own commentary to these comments (because we can't help ourselves) and, naturally, allow you the opportunity to comment on the comments or to comment on our comments about the comments -- in our own comment sections! If that didn't make your head explode, join us. Of course, we can't do it alone, so we ask for your help! The Internet is a yawning gulf of recipes, cat videos, porn and Kanye, and we can't possibly hope to cover it all with our microscopes. So, if, in your perusal of Wolf Blitzer's blog, you see a gem down there in the comment section, tell us about it. You can submit your own comments, images, and videos at TheCommentsSection.com or email Feedback@TheCommentsSection.com. We hope you'll join us -- and click on our ads. We've just launched, so if you have suggestions, please let us know. We're willing to change so that you don't have to. If you're still confused as to what The Comments Section is, think of it like this: We're a comments-section-version of [Texts From Last Night](http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/texts-from-last-night) or [Lamebook](http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/lamebook) (two sites we count as inspiration), plus a place where you can get back at those Web Trolls that keep posting mean things on your blog. Let's get 'em!

Here at UAC Access Control Los Angeles we put all our efforts in to the installation.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: UAC access control offers a wide range of services, but our main overview is giving the consumer a full array to access control products. We can supply single components to all encompassing systems. Our team has the expertise to design and plan a system to not only keep your premises safe but also your staff. The main features of access control systems are usually employed to control locations of where staff members can enter. it is also used to See who is entering and leaving the building and to keep doors locked at all times to non card or fob holders. you will also be able to Set times for individuals to access areas you want them to access at the times that you allow. This is great for shift workers and cleaners and to keep people out on weekends unless they have permission. Standalone access control systems, tend to be made up of a few proximity readers controlled by a nearby doorway control unit. Typically these types of access control networks are used in 1 to 3 doorway installations within a small commercial unit or even a residence. Network Controllers (Computer centered systems) are perfect for large commercial premises such as hospitals, colleges, warehouses, hotels and businesses with a very big workforce. All the card readers on the doors are networked back to main Computer where cards can be programmed to access certain zones. Simple access control systems normally are used to guard one entry way. these range from an electronic lock and magnetic lock, keypad with pin devices, CCTV entry systems and single proximity card entry. These systems are perfect for access to apartment blocks, parking garages and building foyer areas.

Description: Sellathon is the creator of statistics and analytics tools for sellers on third-party sales platforms such as eBay and Overstock.
Full Description: Sellathon is the creator of statistics and analytics tools for sellers on third-party sales platforms such as eBay and Overstock.  Sellathon's most popular product is ViewTracker, a statistics/analytics tool for eBay sellers, which consists of a snippet of javascript that the seller inserts in his or her eBay listings. Once inserted, ViewTracker provides similar user behavior information typically provided by web analytics tools,  but modified for the eBay platform.  Such data includes whether the user was browsing or searching, if searching, which keyword was used to find an item, time spent looking at an item, whether the user is tracking the item in My eBay, etc. Sellathon was founded in 2003 by Wayne Yeager. The company was based in Lexington, Kentucky and had 4 employees. The company was acquired by Auctiva in December 2006, and as of August 2008 had transferred all operations to Chico, California. ViewTracker is now integrated into Auctiva's listing software.
